    .row
      .col-1-2.bg-dk.txt-ff
        .p-md
          .pv-xs.txt-sm.txt-tu.txt-hl= page.title
          .txt-xxl.pv-xs The Government

      .col-1-2.p-md.bg-dk.txt-ff
        .txt-md.txt-border.ph-md.txt-left(style="max-width: 440px")
          :marked
            The Liberal Party has committed to reducing emissions via a
            competition policy using various government funds and agencies
            setup to reduce emissions by investment, loans and grants.  The
            part is aiming for an emissions reduction of 26-28% below 2005
            levels.  The Liberals have also highlighted Australia’s success in
            meeting or exceeding the Kyoto protocol targets. Countries earn
            credits for exceeding the emissions targets at Kyoto that can then
            be carried forward to meet the Paris Climate Agreement targets.
 
    .row
      .col-fw.bg-hl.txt-ff.frame
        .txt-xl.p-md(style="max-width: 720px")
          .bg-bar.bg-ff(style="width: 58%")
          span(data-view="counter") 58% of Australians
          |  rate climate change as a critical threat, third
          | behind international terrorism and North Korea’s nuclear program.
 
  +item(2)
    .row
      .col-1-2.bg-dk.txt-ff
        .p-md
          .pv-xs.txt-sm.txt-tu.txt-hl= page.title
          .txt-xxl.pv-xs The Opposition

      .col-1-2.p-md.bg-dk.txt-ff
        .txt-md.txt-border.ph-md.txt-left(style="max-width: 440px")
          :marked
            The Labor Party has highlighted some government bodies it could use
            to reduce emissions, as part of its climate policy. It has also put
            forward a 45% target for electricity emissions by 2030.  It has
            also been reported that a Labor government will effectively
            introduce a “baseline and credit” emissions credit scheme if
            elected. The party’s plan includes lowering the current government
            emissions cap of 100,000 tonnes of carbon per year to 25,000
            tonnes. This is estimated to affect 250 businesses, up from the 140
            businesses the cap currently covers.   The Labor Party has
            expressed hesitancy on using any Australian credits from the Kyoto
            Protocol to meet the Paris Climate Agreements.

    .row
      .col-1-2.p-md
        .txt-lg.txt-border.ph-md.txt-left(style="max-width: 372px")
          :marked
            Unsurprisingly, the Australian Greens are aiming for net zero, or
            even negative emissions by 2040, as well as binding national
            emissions targets and a moratorium on new coal and gas power
            stations.

      .col-1-2.bg-lt
        .txt-lg.p-md
