      .col-1-2.p-lg
        .block.txt-sans.txt-left
          .pv-md
            :marked
              We all remember Kevin Rudd declaring climate change “the most
              urgent moral challenge of our generation”. It was 2007, and as
              foreign as the concept may seem today, Australia had had the same
              Prime Minister for 11 years.

              At that time, the annual Lowy Institute Poll found that 68% of
              Australians believed global warming was a serious and pressing
              problem, and that we should begin taking steps now, even if this
              involves significant costs. Rudd swept to power with a promise to
              introduce a comprehensive emissions trading scheme.

              But as the drought eased, concerns about climate change waned.
              Rudd’s government lost momentum on emissions legislation and he
              was rolled as Prime Minister. By the time Julia Gillard had
              legislated a price on carbon, the belief that global warming was
              a “serious and pressing problem” had almost halved (36% in 2012).
               
              Climate-sceptic Tony Abbott was elected in 2013 and repealed
              Gillard’s carbon price. Drought conditions also returned to
              Australia in 2013. These events coincide with support for climate
              action rebounding. By 2018, 59% of Australians said steps should
              be taken to address global warming, even at significant cost.

              Australia has been mired in political debates about energy
              security, electricity supply and a once-bipartisan-now-dead
              National Energy Guarantee. The majority of Australians (84%)
              believe the government should focus on renewables, even if this
              means we may need to invest in more infrastructure to make the
              system more reliable (2018).

              In the 2018 Lowy Institute Poll, Australians ranked climate
              change as the third most critical threat to Australia, only
              behind international terrorism and North Korea’s nuclear
              programs. Schoolkids are striking and #climateelection is
              trending. Support for action may not have yet returned to its
              2006 high, but climate change will again be a major election
              issue in 2019.

